SIMPLE: onomatopoeia
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Onomatopoeia
<hw>On`o*mat`o*poe"ia</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr.
<?/; <grk>'o`noma</grk>, <grk>'ono`matos</grk>, a name +
<grk>poiei^n</grk> to make.]</ety> <fld>(Philol.)</fld> <def>The
formation of words in imitation of sounds; a figure of speech in which
the sound of a word is imitative of the sound of the thing which the
word represents; <as>as, the <xex>buzz</xex> of bees; the
<xex>hiss</xex> of a goose; the <xex>crackle</xex> of
fire.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It has been maintained by some philologist that all
primary words, especially names, were formed by imitation of natural
sounds, but this is not believed by most.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Onomatopoeic</ent>⟦br⟧
